\# Loomaa

Semantic Model as Code for Microsoft Fabric / Power BI.

Loomaa provides an end-to-end workflow:

- `loomaa init` ‚Äì scaffold an example project
- `loomaa compile` ‚Äì generate a Fabric/PBIP `.SemanticModel` (TMDL)
- `loomaa view` ‚Äì local interactive model viewer (Streamlit)
- `loomaa deploy` ‚Äì deploy to a Fabric workspace via REST API

## Install

End users:

```bash
pip install loomaa
```

## Quickstart

Create a new project:

```bash
loomaa init my-model
cd my-model
```

Fill in `.env` (created by `init`) with your Fabric IDs:

- `FABRIC_TENANT_ID`
- `FABRIC_CLIENT_ID`
- `FABRIC_CLIENT_SECRET`
- `FABRIC_WORKSPACE_ID`
- `FABRIC_DIRECTLAKE_ITEM_ID`
- `FABRIC_SQL_SERVER`
- `FABRIC_SQL_DATABASE`

Compile the model:

```bash
loomaa compile
```

View the model locally:

```bash
loomaa view
```

Deploy to Fabric:

```bash
loomaa deploy
```

## Output

After `loomaa compile`, output is written under `compiled/`:

- `compiled/<model>/model.json` ‚Äì viewer-friendly JSON
- `compiled/<model>/<model>.SemanticModel/` ‚Äì Fabric/PBIP semantic model artifact

## Repository Layout

This repository uses a standard Python layout:

- `setup.py` / `requirements.txt` live in this folder
- `loomaa/` (package code) contains the CLI, compiler, deploy, and viewer
- `tests/` contains automated tests

